        <section>
            <h2><u>Festi</u>vals</h2>
            <p>North Maharashtra is known for its lively festivals:</p>
        </section>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Makar Sankranti:</strong> A harvest festival celebrated with kite flying and traditional sweets.
            </li>
            <p>
                Makar Sankranti is a significant harvest festival in North Maharashtra, marking the sun's transition
                into Capricorn. This festival, usually celebrated on January 14th, brings families and communities
                together for joyous kite flying, filling the skies with colorful kites. Traditional sweets like tilgul,
                made from sesame and jaggery, are exchanged, symbolizing goodwill and the sweetness of relationships.
            </p>
            <p>
                The celebration extends beyond kite flying, with various fairs and rituals held across rural areas.
                Families visit temples, engage in community gatherings, and enjoy traditional games, showcasing the
                region's rich cultural heritage. Makar Sankranti represents gratitude for the harvest and the importance
                of community spirit, making it a cherished festival in North Maharashtra.
            </p>

            <section>
                <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcS5Xl0EXdcMAxJ6NMm5E8WF_Gz6tUiwd3PX8g&s"
                    alt="Makar Sankranti Celebration" width="600px">
            </section>

            <li><strong>Dussehra:</strong> Celebrated to mark the victory of good over evil, featuring grand
                processions.</li>
            <p>

                Dussehra, also known as Vijayadashami, is a prominent festival celebrated in North Maharashtra, marking
                the victory of good over evil. This ten-day festival culminates on the tenth day, symbolizing Lord
                Rama's triumph over the demon king Ravana. In the region, Dussehra is observed with grandeur, featuring
                elaborate processions, cultural performances, and the traditional burning of effigies representing
                Ravana, symbolizing the eradication of negativity and darkness.</p>
            <p>
                During this festive period, communities come together to participate in various events, including
                reenactments of the Ramayana through drama and dance. Local fairs, known as "Dussehra Melas," are held,
                offering a variety of food, handicrafts, and entertainment. Temples are adorned, and special prayers are
                conducted to seek blessings for strength and prosperity. Dussehra in North Maharashtra reflects a rich
                blend of spirituality, cultural heritage, and community bonding, making it a significant occasion for
                people across the region.
            </p>

