        </ul>

        <section>
            <h2><u>Cui</u>sine</h2>
            <p>North Maharashtra is known for its delicious and diverse cuisine:</p>
        </section>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Bhakri:</strong> A traditional flatbread made from jowar or bajra, often served with chutneys
                and curries.</li>
            <p>
                Bhakri is a traditional flatbread that holds a special place in the cuisine of North Maharashtra. Made
                primarily from coarse grains like jowar (sorghum) or bajra (pearl millet), bhakri is cherished for its
                rustic flavor and nutritional value. The preparation involves kneading the flour with water and rolling
                it into thick discs, which are then cooked on a hot griddle until they develop a slightly crispy
                texture. This hearty bread is often enjoyed with a variety of accompaniments, such as spicy chutneys,
                curries, or traditional vegetable dishes.</p>
            <p>
                In North Maharashtra, bhakri is more than just a staple food; it is a symbol of cultural identity and
                tradition. It is commonly served during festivals, family gatherings, and everyday meals, reflecting the
                region's agricultural roots. Many families take pride in their unique methods of preparing bhakri, often
                passed down through generations.
            </p>

            <section>
                <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcSL7HRndGxmSriZd8wwGusVYWUTC1TImL0eyw&s"
                    alt="Bhakri" width="400px">
            </section>

            <li><strong>Pitla:</strong> A spicy gram flour dish, typically served with bhakri.</li>
            <p>Pitla is a popular dish in North Maharashtra, made from gram flour (besan) and a blend of spices. This
                thick, flavorful curry is often paired with bhakri, creating a delicious and filling meal. Its unique
                texture and taste make it a beloved dish in local households.</p>
            <p>Often garnished with fresh coriander and served with pickles, Pitla showcases the region's culinary
                heritage. It is commonly enjoyed during festivals and family gatherings, reflecting the communal dining
                culture of North Maharashtra.</p>

            <section>
                <img src="https://bongong.com/images/recipes/Pitla/IMG_2459_483902824_center.jpg" alt="Pitla"
                    width="600px">
            </section>

            <li><strong>Khar:</strong> A traditional rice flour snack, often served as a breakfast dish.</li>
            <p>

                Khar is a distinctive dish from North Maharashtra, renowned for its unique flavor and preparation. Made
                primarily with raw bananas, this dish incorporates a blend of spices, such as turmeric, chili powder,
                and garlic, along with a special ingredient called “khar,” which is derived from the alkaline water of
                the plant known as “alu.” The raw bananas are typically boiled and then sautéed with spices, creating a
                savory, aromatic dish that pairs well with rice or bhakri</p>
            <p>Khar is particularly significant in local cuisine, often enjoyed during festive occasions and family
                gatherings. It reflects the region's agricultural practices, as raw bananas are commonly grown in the
                area. This dish not only highlights the creative use of local ingredients but also embodies the essence
                of Maharashtra’s culinary traditions, emphasizing simplicity and bold flavors. Khar remains a beloved
                staple in North Maharashtrian households, cherished for its taste and cultural importance.</p>

